                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="syr-Syre" medium="">
                        <desc>This volume is written in a fine, regular Estrangela of the vith or
                           viith cent.</desc>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote scope="minor" script="syr" medium="">
                        <desc>The exception is fol. 2, which is a paper leaf of the xiith or xiiith
                           cent.</desc>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <p/>
                     <list>
                        <item>
                           <locus from="58b" to=""/>
                           <p>Although this work, Histories of the Solitary Brethren of the Egyptian
                              Desert, is ascribed in the title to <persName
                                 ref="http://syriaca.org/person/668">Palladius</persName>, yet the
                              name of <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/857"
                                 >Hieronymus</persName> is mentioned at the end of each part as
                              being the author.</p>
                           <p><quote xml:lang="syr">ܘܐܢܐ ܐܝܪܘܢܡܝܣ ܚܛ̇ܝܐ ܒ̇ܥܐ ܐܢܐ ܡܢ ܟܠܗܘܢ ܕܩ̇ܪܝܢ
                                 ܒܟܬܒܐ ܗܢܐ ܕܬܨܠܘܢ ܥܠܝ</quote></p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                           <locus from="117b" to=""/>
                           <p>And again, <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/857"
                                 >Hieronymus</persName> is mentioned as the author at the end of
                              Histories of the Solitary Brethren of the Egyptian Desert.</p>
                           <p>
                              <quote xml:lang="syr">ܬܘܒ ܐܢܐ ܐܝܪܘܢܡܝܣ ܚܛܝܐ ܕܐܬܚ̇ܦܛ ܘܟܬ݂ܒ ܬܫ̈ܥܝܬܐ
                                 ܕܗܠܝܢ ܐܒܗ̈ܬܐ ܩܕܝ̈ܫܐ̣. ܒ̇ܥܐ ܐܢܐ ܡܢ ܟܠܗܘܢ ܕܩܪܝܢ ܒܟܬܒܐ ܗܢܐ̣ ܕܢܨ̇ܠܘܢ
                                 ܥܠܝ.</quote>
                           </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                           <locus from="" to=""/>
                           <p>Some portions of this work have been edited by pupils of the late
                              Professor Tullberg of Upsala, under the title of "Libri qui
                              inscribitur Paradisus Patrum partes selectae," Upsala, 1851; viz.— 1.
                                 <persName>John of Lycos</persName>. See fol. 118 b. 2. <persName
                                 ref="http://syriaca.org/person/13">Ephraim, deacon of <placeName
                                    ref="http://syriaca.org/place/78">Edessa</placeName></persName>.
                              See fol. 124 b. 3. <persName>Chronius of <placeName
                                    ref="http://syriaca.org/place/151"
                                 >Phoenicia</placeName></persName>. See fol. 121 b. 4. <persName
                                 ref="http://syriaca.org/person/1799">Jacob the lame</persName>
                              <xml:lang ref="syr">(ܚܓܝܪܐ)</xml:lang>. See fol. 121 b. 5. <persName
                                 ref=" http://syriaca.org/person/1982">Paul, the disciple of
                                    <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/1594"
                                 >Antony</persName></persName>, and 6. <persName
                                 ref="http://syriaca.org/person/1955">Pachomius</persName>; both
                              apparently wanting in this manuscript. 7. On holy women. See fol. 126
                              b. 8. The virgin <xml:lang ref="syr">ܛܡܝܪܘܢ</xml:lang> (or
                                 <persName>Taor</persName>). See fol. 127 b. 9. The virgin
                                 <persName>Colluthus</persName> (<!--missing Greek-->). See fol. 127
                              b. 10. A virgin who fell and repented. See fol. 135 a. 11.
                                 <persName>Abba Elias</persName>. See fol. 136 a. </p>
                           <p>
                              <quote xml:lang="syr"/>
                           </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                           <locus from="" to=""/>
                           <p>From the above, and from the table of contents given by Assemani in
                              the Bibl. Orient., t. i., p. 608, we perceive that the Syriac copies
                              of this work differ as much from one another as the Greek.</p>
                           <p>
                              <quote xml:lang="syr"/>
                           </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                           <locus from="" to=""/>
                           <p>On fol. 1 a there is a note statins' that the manuscript belonged to
                              one <persName>Simeon bar Had- be-shabba</persName>, from <placeName
                                 ref=" http://syriaca.org/place/411">Salamya</placeName> (ܣܠܡܝܐ,
                              <!--missing Arabic-->).</p>
                           <p>
                              <quote xml:lang="syr">ܐܝܬܘܗܝ ܟܬܒܐ ܗܢܐ ܠܫܡܥܘܢ ܒܪ ܚܕܒܫܒܐ ܕܡܢ ܣܠܡܝܐ
                                 ܡܕܝܢܬܐ ܕܣܡܗ ܠܡܩܪܐ ܒܗ. ܐܠܐ ܟܠ ܡܢ ܕܫ̇ܩܠ ܠܗ ܏ܘܫ.</quote>
                           </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                           <locus from="" to=""/>
                           <p>A note on fol. 181 b mentions that it was bequeathed by him to the
                                 <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/360">convent of S. Mary
                                 Deipara.</placeName>.</p>
                           <p>
                              <quote xml:lang="syr">ܐܝܬܘܗܝ ܟܬܒܐ ܗܢܐ ܕܕܝܪܐ ܕܣܘܪ̈ܝܝܐ ܕܒܡܕܒܪܐ. ܫܟܢܗ ܕܝܢ
                                 ܠܗ̇ ܠܕܝܪܐ ܒܪ ܚܕܒܫܒܐ ܡܢܚܐ ܕܐܠܗܐ ܢܚܣܐ ܠܗ. ܘܠܐ ܫܠܝܛ ܠܐܢܫ ܕܢܦܩܗ ܡܢ ܕܝܪܐ
                                 ܏ܘܫ.</quote>
                           </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                           <locus from="" to=""/>
                           <p>There is another note on the same page, apparently of older date than
                              either of the above, but mutilated, which states that the book
                              belonged to one <persName>David</persName> the son of-: The words
                                 <xml:lang ref="syr">ܕܕܘܝܕ ܒܪ</xml:lang> are, however, clearly a
                              later alteration.</p>
                           <p>
                              <quote xml:lang="syr">ܐܝܬܘܗܝ ܕܝܢ ܟܬܒܐ ܗܢܐ ܕܕܘܝܕ ܒܪ . . . ܐܠܐ ܟܠ ܡܢ
                                 ܕܫܩܠ ܠܗ ܕܢܩܪܐ ܒܗ ܏ܘܫ.</quote>
                           </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                           <locus from="" to=""/>
                           <p>On fol. 59 a there is written in a hand of the xiith or xiiith
                              cent.</p>
                           <p>
                              <quote xml:lang="syr">ܒܫܡܐ ܕܐܠܗܐ ܚ̇ܢ̣ܢܐ. ܐܢܐ ܐܢܫ ܚܛܝܐ ܘܕܘܝܐ ܕܟܠܗܘܢ
                                 ܒܢܝ̈ܢܫܐ ܕܐܝܬ ܥܠ ܐܪܥܐ. ܕܩ̇ܪܝܬ ܒܟܬܒܐ ܗܢܐ ܩܠܝܠ ܘܝ̇ܬܪܬ ܡܢܗ. ܘܡܛܠܗܕܐ
                                 ܟܬܒ̇ܬ ܥܘܗܕܢܐ ܗܢܐ. ܘܡܦܝܣ ܐܢ̣ܐ ܘܡܬܟܫܦ ܐܢܐ ܘܡܬܓܪܓܚ ܐܢܐ ܩܕܡ ܟܠ ܡ̇ܢ
                                 ܕܩ̇ܪܐ ܗܠܝܢ ܣܘܪ̈ܛܐ ܒ̈ܠܝ̣ܠܐ ܘܒ̈ܠܝܓܐ ܕܢܨ̇ܠܐ ܥܠ ܚܛܝܘܬܝ ܘܕܘܝܘܬܝ
                                 ܏ܘܫ.</quote>
                           </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                           <locus from="" to=""/>
                           <p>On fol. 178 a there is a note informing us that the <persName>bishop
                                 Abraham</persName> came with certain monks from the
                                 <placeName>convent of Natpha</placeName> to that of <placeName
                                 ref="http://syriaca.org/place/360">S. Mary Deipara</placeName>, on
                              Saturday, the 5th of Iyar, A. Gr. 1630, A.D. 1319. </p>
                           <p>
                              <quote xml:lang="syr">ܡܛܝܢ ܠܡܕܒܪܐ ܐܘܟܝܬ ܠܕܝܪܐ ܕܝܠܢ ܣܘܪ̈ܝܝܐ ܐ̇ܢܐ ܐܒܪܗܡ
                                 ܒܫܡ ܚܣܝܐ ܘܐܚ̈ܐ ܕܡܢ ܢ̇ܛܦܐ ܪܒܢ ܝܘܚܢܢ ܘܪܒܢ ܐܝܘܢܝܣ ܐܚ̈ܐ ܕܡ̈ܢܝܐ ܘܩ̈ܫܝܫ
                                 (sic) ܙܗ̈ܝܐ ܘܪܒܢ ܝܘܣܦ ܘܪܒܢ ܝܘܚܢܢ ܝܘܡ ܫܒܬܐ ܏ܗ ܒܐܝܪ ܫܢܬ ܐ܏ܘܣܘܠ
                                 ܒܕܝܘ̈ܢܝܐ.</quote>
                           </p>
                        </item>
